Editor=E2=80=99s note: Taylor Swift=E2=80=99s The Life of a Showgirl has do=
minated charts, airwaves, and social feeds alike=E2=80=94including Substack=
=E2=80=99s. We asked essayist and critic BDM to make sense of the album and=
 Swift=E2=80=99s singular ability to drive the discourse.
With her newest album, The Life of a Showgirl, Taylor Swift has the number =
one song, the number one album, and the number one movie in America. She=E2=
=80=99s the first artist to achieve this feat; not even Prince=E2=80=99s  [=
 https://substack.com/redirect/c3de9613-7612-4605-aa23-ef5908ca97a2?j=3DeyJ=
1IjoiMW5qZ29rIn0.AgI-vvm-koCoupjCwZXCGwdYu_D1iw9ecHmePkbA3ys ]Purple Rain [=
 https://substack.com/redirect/c3de9613-7612-4605-aa23-ef5908ca97a2?j=3DeyJ=
1IjoiMW5qZ29rIn0.AgI-vvm-koCoupjCwZXCGwdYu_D1iw9ecHmePkbA3ys ] reached thes=
e heights [ https://substack.com/redirect/c3de9613-7612-4605-aa23-ef5908ca9=
7a2?j=3DeyJ1IjoiMW5qZ29rIn0.AgI-vvm-koCoupjCwZXCGwdYu_D1iw9ecHmePkbA3ys ]. =
She=E2=80=99s set to blow past Adele=E2=80=99s first-week sales record of 3=
 and a half million albums. Swift=E2=80=99s fame and commercial success mig=
ht make this seem like no big deal=E2=80=94sure, we could all sell 3 millio=
n albums if we were that famous=E2=80=94but that gets the causality backwar=
d. She only hits marks like these because she treats every release like suc=
cess has to be earned all over again. As a longtime fan, I often roll my ey=
es at the stunts she pulls to make sure her fans buy the album: the multipl=
e variants, the exclusive tracks, the carefully timed announcements. But I =
also buy the album, and so, apparently, do a lot of other people.
No current pop figure is as in control of their career as Swift is=E2=80=94=
directing her own music videos, owning her masters, dictating when and how =
she releases music. That kind of control is only possible because she=E2=80=
=99s reached a rare level of fame that shapes the conversation, whether peo=
ple want to participate in it or not. For instance: you=E2=80=99re reading =
this post, even if you=E2=80=99re grumbling to yourself about how tired you=
 are of hearing about Taylor Swift. You wouldn=E2=80=99t be here for someon=
e else. It=E2=80=99s no fun to be exasperated at somebody else.
Swift=E2=80=99s been singing about her difficult relationship with fame sin=
ce =E2=80=9CThe Lucky One=E2=80=9D on Red (2012), a track that asks, Wouldn=
=E2=80=99t it be nice to throw all this over and just be a girl with her gu=
itar? She followed up Red with the smash hit album 1989, which implicitly a=
nswered this question with: nah. A concept album about being a showgirl sho=
uld be a perfect fit for her themes. Every text about show business is also=
 a text about fame and contains the following message: show business is the=
 worst thing in the world, and it=E2=80=99s the only thing worth doing. Sho=
w business involves precarity on a level that goes beyond the financial=E2=
=80=94show to show, crowd to crowd, you stake everything every time and put=
 the fate of your performance in the hands of people who may be barely payi=
ng attention. (One edition of Showgirl is titled =E2=80=9CThe Crowd Is Your=
 King.=E2=80=9D)
Swift clearly loves being famous, and she also, just as clearly, hates bein=
g famous. Anyone who=E2=80=99s seen Taylor Swift on a stage can see how she=
 pulls strength from the crowd; anyone can also see the downsides of living=
 her life (stalkers, surveillance, the dissolution of private life). She pe=
rformed her Eras Tour routines sick, with a chunk of her hand missing [ htt=
ps://substack.com/redirect/669d8a88-19aa-4961-b0bb-4f725ddde555?j=3DeyJ1Ijo=
iMW5qZ29rIn0.AgI-vvm-koCoupjCwZXCGwdYu_D1iw9ecHmePkbA3ys ], and through a h=
eel breaking off her shoe=E2=80=94the kind of dedication that=E2=80=99s nei=
ther love nor compulsion, but both. That double-edged devotion to the stage=
 should be the beating heart of an album about the life of a showgirl.
But for all of its pleasures, Showgirl only flirts with that theme. So let=
=E2=80=99s cut to the chase: it=E2=80=99s a fun album, just not a great one=
=2E It feels more like a little treat t=
o keep the fans tided over while Swift=
 prepares to spend a few years focused on her personal life=E2=80=94a diges=
tif after the heavy meal of the Eras Tour and The Tortured Poets Department=
=E2=80=94than it does a full artistic project on its own.
The love songs are sweet=E2=80=94=E2=80=9COpalite,=E2=80=9D with its invoca=
tion of false and true loves and its girl-group flourishes, is about to rul=
e every wedding dance floor for the next five years. =E2=80=9CWood,=E2=80=
=9D where Swift runs through every dick joke you can think of (and a few yo=
u definitely couldn=E2=80=99t) is cheekily and euphorically sexual. The ven=
geful songs are unapologetically acid, and all the better for it. In the pa=
st, Swift=E2=80=99s had a tendency to work the refs if she wanted to settle=
 a score, but now she just settles the scores herself. In Lover=E2=80=99s =
=E2=80=9CThe Man,=E2=80=9D Swift complained that if she were a man, people =
would like her more; now, in =E2=80=9CFather Figure,=E2=80=9D she takes on =
a mob-boss persona and sends an enemy to sleep with the fishes. Who cares a=
bout being liked, anyway? Not Vito Corleone. In Old Hollywood, they sometim=
es called women like Swift=E2=80=94ultra-feminine artists with a keen eye f=
or business and a long memory for wrongs=E2=80=94steel butterflies. They=E2=
=80=99re my favorites, and all of this adds up to a good time.
But what is this album about, really? It was supposed to be about the offst=
age part of the showgirl life, but there=E2=80=99s little of that to be fou=
nd. There=E2=80=99s the title track=E2=80=94a duet with Sabrina Carpenter=
=E2=80=94an ode to showgirl life and the fickleness of the crowd. =E2=80=9C=
Elizabeth Taylor,=E2=80=9D the album=E2=80=99s second track and its best, i=
s the only other song that directly discusses fame and the effect it has on=
 Swift=E2=80=99s life. It=E2=80=99s framed as a conversation with Elizabeth=
 Taylor=E2=80=99s invisible presence, as Swift sings that whether or not an=
y love lasts forever for her, it certainly lasts forever in the minds of ot=
hers.
=E2=80=9CElizabeth Taylor=E2=80=9D is a wonderful song, with one of the alb=
um=E2=80=99s cleverest lines (=E2=80=9CI=E2=80=99d cry my eyes violet,=E2=
=80=9D as in, she=E2=80=99d cry so much her blue eyes would become so blood=
shot, they=E2=80=99d be purple, thus resembling Elizabeth Taylor=E2=80=99s=
=E2=80=94it=E2=80=99s better how she says it). But two songs isn=E2=80=99t =
much, and that brings us to the album=E2=80=99s other flaw. As the Eras Tou=
r demonstrated, Taylor Swift has many selves, and many artistic sides. Ther=
e=E2=80=99s Taylor the storyteller, with her country roots; there=E2=80=99s=
 Taylor the pop monster. The first Taylor gave us lines like =E2=80=9CYou m=
ade a rebel of a careless man=E2=80=99s careful daughter,=E2=80=9D lines th=
at contained a whole world through her use of careful detail. The second Ta=
ylor knows how to write a song you want to turn up on the radio=E2=80=94but=
 these hits have often come at the sacrifice of detail. One of the promises=
 of Showgirl was that it would unite these halves.
So, does it? Some songs, yes; some songs, no. The aforementioned =E2=80=9CO=
palite,=E2=80=9D for instance, opens, =E2=80=9CI had a bad habit of missing=
 lovers past / my brother used to call it, =E2=80=98Eating out of the trash=
=E2=80=99=E2=80=9D=E2=80=94this is a classic detail. But =E2=80=9CHoney,=E2=
=80=9D a song about how her new lover has taken all the terms that used to =
feel passive-aggressive and made them feel real, is the kind of song that s=
hould feel rooted in detail. That a word could be transformed when said by =
the right person is the kind of experience Swift specializes in bringing to=
 life. But the people who poisoned words like =E2=80=9Csweetheart=E2=80=9D =
are generic mean girls and bad guys; the new guy who says it and means it a=
lso doesn=E2=80=99t feel real. It=E2=80=99s a nice song, and it has some of=
 Swift=E2=80=99s most heartfelt vocals on Showgirl, but it could have been =
a better one.
On the other hand, some of her lyrics on this album are cringe in a way tha=
t is ultimately one of Swift=E2=80=99s virtues. Swift=E2=80=99s gift as a l=
yricist, aside from her storytelling, is her ability to take objects in our=
 verbal culture=E2=80=94Ophelia, TikTok memes, stock turns of speech=E2=80=
=94and combine them and turn them inside out. Perhaps even more than she lo=
ves music, Taylor Swift loves language. She loves double meanings, flipped =
meanings, puns; she loves language in all its sonic dimensions. She=E2=80=
=99ll willfully mix a metaphor, because she knows the jarring contrast betw=
een images can create something more memorable than a perfect line. There=
=E2=80=99s a lot of crude imagery on Showgirl, and there=E2=80=99s been a l=
ot of tittering about it, but many of these moments are serving a purpose. =
=E2=80=9CI can make deals with the devil because my dick=E2=80=99s bigger,=
=E2=80=9D from =E2=80=9CFather Figure,=E2=80=9D wields its blunt language o=
ver George Michael interpolation and an otherwise sophisticated self-presen=
tation. These lyrics look bad written out=E2=80=94but that=E2=80=99s fine. =
Lyrics are supposed to go with music, not stand alone.
Much like Swift=E2=80=99s Lover, a very uneven album with some of Swift=E2=
=80=99s best songs (=E2=80=9CCruel Summer,=E2=80=9D =E2=80=9CCornelia Stree=
t=E2=80=9D) and her worst (=E2=80=9CLondon Boy,=E2=80=9D =E2=80=9CYou Need =
to Calm Down=E2=80=9D), The Life of a Showgirl is an uneven album, but this=
 time without career highs or career lows. Like Midnights, it has a strong =
opening half with a weaker back end. Taken together, what this trilogy of g=
ood-but-flawed pop albums suggests=E2=80=94at least to this writer=E2=80=94=
is that there=E2=80=99s not much left for Taylor Swift in the world of pure=
 pop music. She has sucked that marrow dry. In the =E2=80=9Canthology=E2=80=
=9D edition of The Tortured Poets Department, she=E2=80=99s also explored w=
hat was left in the sonic world of folklore. What I=E2=80=99m saying is tha=
t whenever she comes back with album 13, Taylor Swift needs to pick up an e=
lectric guitar. It=E2=80=99s time.
As it is, The Life of a Showgirl is a victory lap. This is what it looks li=
ke to win in just about every way a human being can. Swift knows as well as=
 anybody else that what goes up must come down, but when you=E2=80=99re up,=
 you=E2=80=99re up. Might as well have fun. After all=E2=80=94how many of y=
ou clicked on this to read an album review? That=E2=80=99s not what anybody=
 wants to read. They want a review of Swift, the person. They=E2=80=99re ge=
tting that review on every social media platform in the world right now. He=
re it is: A lot of people hate Swift. They are tired of seeing her face. Th=
ey are tired of hearing her voice. They comb through the album for signs th=
at Swift is not only a bad artist but a bad person. Stacked against the mea=
surable response to the album=E2=80=94the sales and the streams=E2=80=94the=
ir hatred doesn=E2=80=99t really signify, which only intensifies matters. O=
ne line is that Swift is only so popular because she=E2=80=99s so mediocre =
that she gives her equally mediocre fans something to aspire to. But at the=
 risk of sounding cute, there are a lot of mediocre people, and there=E2=80=
=99s only one Taylor Swift. Magic Eight Ball says: Try again.
Fame is fickle, but Taylor Swift has proven uniquely adept at riding its wa=
ves. If she=E2=80=99s treading water with this album, and she is, onlookers=
 would be very foolish to think she=E2=80=99s sinking. Everyone should have=
 learned this lesson years ago=E2=80=94Taylor Swift, up or down, is never o=
ver. Did I say get ready to hear =E2=80=9COpalite=E2=80=9D at every wedding=
 for the next five years? Make it 10.

